\fs28 \cf4 \'97\'97\'97\'97\'97\'97\'97 CREDITS \'97\'97\'97\'97\'97\'97\'97\'97
\fs24 \cf2 \
\
This program was started as an effort to implement a graphical presentation of an XDS Sigma-7 running Control Program Five (CP-V).\
\
I had come across the Windows XP \'93siggy\'94 program by George Plue and Keith Calkins some years earlier and after retiring I decided it would be amusing to implement a Sigma emulator for my Mac.  The XP implementation conveniently came with a collection of source code for both the emulator and CP-V itself.\
\
I used the XP emulator to build disk images for the C0F version for which there was a PO \'93tape\'94, and started work on the Mac-based emulator (in Swift, which I had not used before but decided was worth learning).\
\
After about a year of inconsistent attention to the project, I was able to boot CP-V from the disk images, logon, and run a few simple programs.  The implementation had a graphical representation of a running Sigma-7 panel, and a fairly extensive debugger for the virtual machine.  I made a video of this:\
\
\pard\tx593\pardeftab593\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://drive.google.com/file/d/13axGAJYOo_VJbMYL8kOx-wxzT3pq8cL7/view?usp=share_link"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 https://drive.google.com/file/d/13axGAJYOo_VJbMYL8kOx-wxzT3pq8cL7/view?usp=share_link}}\
\
I sent the video to Keith Calkins, who passed it along to various interested parties.  They made me aware of the SIMH project and the associated Sigma/CP-V work that was being done by Ken Rector in particular.  Although I have not used SIMH or its code base, it has on a couple of occasions been helpful as a reference for debugging unexpected behaviour from my own emulation code.  Ken's {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/kenrector/sigma-cpv-kit"}}{\fldrslt sigma-cpv-kit}} was particularly useful in providing F00 sysgen tapes and utilities.\
\pard\tx593\pardeftab593\partightenfactor0
